      • buildAlleles

        private java.lang.String buildAlleles​(Gene[] rawGenes)
        Builds the Alleles for all the genes in the array. Checks the boolean values for each gene to indicate which type of Alleles should be expressed. Then it concatenates them into one string.
        Parameters:
        rawGenes - Gene[]
        Returns:
        result String

      • buildAlleleCombinations

        private java.lang.String[] buildAlleleCombinations​(java.lang.String alleles)
        Takes in a String of characters representing Genes in order of Dominant to recessive. Capital letters indicate dominant genes, conversely lower case letters indicate recessive genes. 2 letters per gene, up to 5 genes. Must be same 2 letters for each gene (i.e. Aa, AA, or aa)
        Parameters:
        alleles - String
        Returns:
        combinations String[]

      • buildAlleleCombinations

        private java.lang.String[] buildAlleleCombinations​(java.lang.String[] result,
                                                   java.lang.String alleles)
        Recursive overload method to crawl through the alleles String, process two letters--corresponding to a Gene, add them to the new String[] to make sure any aA gets changed to Aa. Then removes the two letters it just processed and recurse.
        Parameters:
        result - String[]
        alleles - String
        Returns:
        combinations String[]

      • buildPunnettSquare

        private void buildPunnettSquare​(java.lang.String[] parentOne,
                                java.lang.String[] parentTwo)
        Builds a Punnett Square with the results String[] from buildAlleleCombinations. The Punnett Square is a square with each Combination of one parent on the X axis, and each combination of the other parent on the Y axis. Going row by row checking for any upper case characters, as they represent dominant alleles. If there's one dominant allele, it needs to be the first letter. Otherwise, the letter case doesn't matter, so it adds to the current String. As it recurses, it goes deeper into the Punnett Square, adding the combinations to the end of the String result. For example, if you have combinations Ab and AB, the result comes out as AABb.
        Parameters:
        parentOne - String[]
        parentTwo - String[]
